text:
@Fernando-ek8jp Honestly, I think there's a Motorola and a few others that have the same rating and I don't THINK there are any that budget that are higher. I think at about the 300 range is when the ratings start to come in for new, but keep in mind you can get used phones with higher ratings in that range as well. I'd probably get a used Pixel 6A or new during a super sale or something similar before this. 

Maybe if I actually see this phone I'd trust it more, but considering the case is basically "screwed" on I'd personally trust it less than budget phones I've used in the past. It's a nice gimmick. I guess you could argue being able to replace the covers is "better" but considering how cheaply you can buy solid phone cases the ability to switch covers feels pointless to me. Like if the battery was removeable and I could buy a sturdy cover with more protection I'd be interested. 

But that's just me. It's fine, but I've been looking at getting a cheap phone and it's not something I'd personally be interested in.

@restoresto2039Yes! They should have provided you with 108 MP periscope camera, a 50 MP ultra wide camera, SD 8 Gen 3 SOC, 150W wired and 50W wireless charging, 7 years or major OS update at $200.

Speaking of accessories, which you mentioned them as gimmick, those accessories don't come inside the box, they sold separately. More or less even company sell 1st part accessories, no one will force you to buy those thing useless you want to. 

Yeah, they missed the opportunity, they lost a talented, tech enthusiast customer like you.

200? It's literally about double the price here in Sweden, $389 🥹😂

EDIT;
apparently was looking at the wrong phone. The right one is $289
